TY  - JOUR
T1  - Who Controls Whom? An Examination of the Relation Between Management and Boards of Directors in Large American Corporations
AU  - Mizruchi, Mark S.
Y1  - 1983/07/01
PY  - 1983
DA  - 1983/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1983.4284426
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1983.4284426
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 426
EP  - 435
VL  - 8
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Most organization theorists believe that boards of directors in large American corporations are dominated by management. This paper argues that this view is based on a problematic definition of control. Several distinctions between long run and short run control are presented, and a framework in which boards of directors have control over managers is suggested. Case examples are given and possible objections are confronted. Finally, an agenda for further research on board-management relations is offered.
AB  - Most organization theorists believe that boards of directors in large American corporations are dominated by management. This paper argues that this view is based on a problematic definition of control. Several distinctions between long run and short run control are presented, and a framework in which boards of directors have control over managers is suggested. Case examples are given and possible objections are confronted. Finally, an agenda for further research on board-management relations is offered.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1983.4284426
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1983.4284426
Y2  - 2026/04/24
