T1  - Self-Management: Its Control and Relationship to Other Organizational Properties
AU  - Mills, Peter K.
Y1  - 1983/07/01
PY  - 1983
DA  - 1983/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1983.4284594
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1983.4284594
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 445
EP  - 453
VL  - 8
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Current models on self-management in organizations generally have taken a bivariate perspective. This paper proposes a more complex conceptualization of self-management in which its control mechanisms are examined. It is argued that the self-managed employee is far from loosely supervised; such employee is closely controlled. It is argued further that the clientele's active participation in the operation of the organization mediates the widely held relationship between self-management and structure.
AB  - Current models on self-management in organizations generally have taken a bivariate perspective. This paper proposes a more complex conceptualization of self-management in which its control mechanisms are examined. It is argued that the self-managed employee is far from loosely supervised; such employee is closely controlled. It is argued further that the clientele's active participation in the operation of the organization mediates the widely held relationship between self-management and structure.
